# ============================================================
# Performance & Verification
# ============================================================
performance: {
  label: "Verification & Tooling"
  
  bench: {
    label: "Verify Cache Behavior"
    style.fill: "#F3E5F5"
    code: |'bash
      # Check for jemalloc
      ldd ./particle_sim | grep jemalloc

      # Measure cache misses
      perf stat -e L1-dcache-load-misses ./particle_sim
    '|
  }
}

false_sharing -> performance

# ============================================================
# Summary
# ============================================================
summary: {
  label: "Summary: Linking Slabs to Implementation"
  width: 750
  style.fill: "#E8F5E9"
  style.stroke: "#4CAF50"
  style.stroke-width: 3
  takeaways: |'md
    1. **Size Classes**: jemalloc treats allocations of similar sizes identically, easing layout planning.
    2. **Slab Alignment**: Slabs are page-aligned; slots are bin-aligned (e.g., 64-byte bins = cache alignment).
    3. **Spatial Locality**: Contiguous arrays (like our SoA `x[]`, `y[]`) fit neatly into slabs/pages.
    4. **Manual Control**: Use `aligned_alloc(64, ...)` for SIMD (AVX/AVX-512) to ensure hardware constraints are met regardless of the underlying allocator implementation.
  '|
}

performance -> summary

